03497nam a22005055i 9780804768252DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047682527 a10.1515/97808047682522doi  a(DE-B1597)581633  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aF1221.N3bT48 2007eb 7aHIS0250002bisacsh04a972/.530049745222200aTestaments of Toluca /ced. by Caterina Pizzigoni. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Notaries in the Corpus -- tList of Testaments in Clusters -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroductory Study -- t1. Characteristics of the Corpus -- t2. The Wills and What They Tell Us -- t3. Language and Orthography -- t4. Notaries -- t5. Some Concluding Remarks -- tTestaments of Toluca: Transcription, Translation, and Commentary -- tToluca Area -- tTepemaxalco -- tCalimaya -- tCalimaya/Tepemaxalco -- tGlossary -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTestaments written in their own language, Nahuatl, have been crucial for reconstructing the everyday life of the indigenous people of central Mexico after Spanish contact. Those published to date have largely been from the sixteenth and early seventeenth centuries. Testaments of Toluca presents a large body of Nahuatl wills (98) from 1652 to 1783 from an important valley not much studied, thus greatly enlarging our perspective on the evolution of indigenous society and culture in central Mexico. Each testament is transcribed, translated, and accompanied by a commentary on the testator's situation and on interesting terminology. A substantial introductory study fully analyzes the testamentary genre as seen in this corpus (a first) and summarizes the content of the documents in realms such as gender, kinship, household, and land. Wills are very human documents, and the apparatus draws out this aspect, telling us much of local indigenous life in central Mexico in the third century after Spanish contact, so that the book is of potential interest to a broad spectrum of readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aNahuasxHistoryvSources. 0aNahuaszMexicozToluca de LerdoxHistoryvSources. 0aWillszMexicozToluca de Lerdo. 4aAnthropology -- Latin America. 4aHistory -- Latin American. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh1 aPizzigoni, Caterina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804768252zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804768252423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804768252/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles